'''David Baumgardt''' (20 April 1890 - 21 21, 1963)was a early 20th century German Jewish [[philosopher]] in the field of philosophical history. He was a professor of Philosophy at the University of Berlin.<ref name="SkolnikBerenbaum2007">{{cite book|author1=Fred Skolnik|author2=Michael Berenbaum|title=Encyclopaedia Judaica, Volume 1|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=MbNYAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA54|year=2007|publisher=Granite Hill Publishers|isbn=978-0-02-865929-9|pages=54<U+2013>}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Baumgardt was born in Erfurt, German Empire.  As a young man he studied at the University of Friedberg and served in the military during World War I.<ref name="ScholemDavid2007">{{cite book|author1=Gershom Scholem|author2=Anthony David|title=Lamentations of Youth: The Diaries of Gershom Scholem, 1913-1919|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=QSGHABOOFhAC&pg=PA355|year=2007|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-02669-8|pages=355<U+2013>}}</ref>

==Career==
Baumgardt's main field of studies was ancient philosophy and Ethics. He wrote about the relationship between ethical and religious ideology.<ref name="Iannone2013">{{cite book|author=A. Pablo Iannone|title=Dictionary of World Philosophy|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=AyB6GXM-CZkC&pg=PT614|date=15 April 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-68043-6|pages=614<U+2013>}}</ref>

In 1965 he wrote a retrospective of his years at the University of Berlin, entitled, ''Looking Back on a German University Career''.<ref name="Feuer1974">{{cite book|author=Lewis Samuel Feuer|title=Einstein and the Generations of Science|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=_6zauDvo78sC&pg=PA82|year=1974|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-1-4128-2235-0|pages=82<U+2013>}}</ref>

Later in his life he was a consultant in philosophy to the American [[Library of Congress]].<ref name="Reisch2005">{{cite book|author=George A. Reisch|title=How the Cold War Transformed Philosophy of Science: To the Icy Slopes of Logic|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=uhahmUJndWMC&pg=PA162|date=21 March 2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-54689-8|pages=162<U+2013>}}</ref>

Many  commentaries were written about his work, including ''David Baumgardt and ethical hedonism'' by Zeev Levy and also ''Aristotle Ethical views'' by ''Mehdi Shokri''.

==Legacy==
Baumgardt died in [[Long Beach]][[, New York]], [[USA]]. 

A fellowship is offered by the Leo Baeck Institute, which houses a collection of his papers, to students who study and extend Baumgardt's work.<ref name="LLC2008">{{cite book|author=Schoolhouse Partners LLC|title=Directory of Research Grants 2008|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Z7e99f1wKjIC&pg=PA17|date=May 2008|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4343-4698-8|pages=17<U+2013>}}</ref>

== Main Works ==

*''Franz v. Baader und die philosophische Romantik'', 1927. 
*''Der Kampf um den Lebenssinn unter Vorl<U+00E4>ufern der modernen Ethik'', 1933.
*''Bentham and the Ethica of Today'', 1952. 
*''Great Western Mystics and their Lasting Significance'', 1961. 
*''Die abendl<U+00E4>ndische Mystik'', 1963.

